Q1. Who has written “Acceptance Speech”?
(a) Aung San Suu Kyi
(b) R. C. Hutchinson
(c) Toni Morrison
(d) Mahadevi Verma
Correct Answer: (a) Aung San Suu Kyi
Explanation: The speech is written by Aung San Suu Kyi, but it was delivered by her son Alexander Aris because she was under house arrest in Burma.
Q2. The beauty of genuine brotherhood and peace is more precious than—
(a) diamonds
(b) gold
(c) silver
(d) All of the above
Correct Answer: (d) All of the above
Explanation: The speech says that peace and brotherhood are more valuable than gold, silver, and diamonds because they are material things but peace is priceless.
Q3. Acceptance speech was delivered on December 10 —
(a) 1991
(b) 1992
(c) 1990
(d) 1993
Correct Answer: (a) 1991
Explanation: Nobel Peace Prize ceremony is held on 10 December every year. Her speech was delivered on 10 December 1991 in Oslo.
Q4. Burma’s long struggle is for —
(a) Peace only
(b) Freedom only
(c) Peace, freedom and democracy
(d) Food and security
Correct Answer: (c) Peace, freedom and democracy
Explanation: The people of Burma were fighting against military rule to achieve democracy, freedom, and peace.
Q5. Alexander Aris delivered the speech in —
(a) Tokyo
(b) Oslo
(c) Delhi
(d) None
Correct Answer: (b) Oslo
Explanation: Nobel Peace Prize ceremony takes place in Oslo, Norway. So the speech was delivered there.
Q6. Who was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1991?
(a) Alexander Aris
(b) A. P. J. Abdul Kalam
(c) Aung San Suu Kyi
(d) None
Correct Answer: (c) Aung San Suu Kyi
Explanation: She received the Nobel Peace Prize for her non-violent struggle for democracy in Burma.
Q7. Aris firmly believed that his mother would have accepted the prize for all the —
(a) people
(b) monks
(c) politicians
(d) soldiers
Correct Answer: (a) people
Explanation: She accepted the award on behalf of all the people of Burma, not for herself.
Q8. Aung San Suu Kyi was a famous — politician.
(a) Indian
(b) Burmese
(c) African
(d) Chinese
Correct Answer: (b) Burmese
Explanation: She was the leader of Myanmar (Burma) and fought for democracy there.
Q9. Who received the Nobel Prize awarded to Aung San Suu Kyi?
(a) Her mother
(b) Her daughter
(c) Her son
(d) Her sister
Correct Answer: (c) Her son
Explanation: Her son Alexander Aris received the Nobel Prize because she was under house arrest.
Q10. Humanity cannot be bound to — and war. (Martin Luther King Jr.)
(a) dictatorship
(b) racism
(c) torture
(d) autocracy
Correct Answer: (b) racism
Explanation: Martin Luther King Jr. said humanity cannot be bound to racism and war; humanity should live in peace and equality.
Q11. Aung San Suu Kyi belongs to —
(a) Bangladesh
(b) Myanmar
(c) Malaysia
(d) Indonesia
Correct Answer: (b) Myanmar
Explanation: Myanmar is the new name of Burma.
Q12. Aung San Suu Kyi struggled for —
(a) an autocratic Burma
(b) a socialist Burma
(c) a democratic Burma
(d) a communist Burma
Correct Answer: (c) a democratic Burma
Explanation: She fought for democracy and human rights.
Q13. Nobel Peace Prize is all about ideals of —
(a) freedom
(b) peace
(c) humanism
(d) democracy
Correct Answer: (c) humanism
Explanation: The Nobel Peace Prize represents human dignity, freedom, peace, and human values.
Q14. She struggled for — of human spirit.
(a) separation
(b) participation
(c) suppression
(d) emancipation
Correct Answer: (d) emancipation
Explanation: Emancipation means freedom from political, social, or legal restrictions.
Q15. Nobel Peace Prize helped Burmese people to — their heads higher.
(a) raise
(b) hold
(c) lower
(d) hang
Correct Answer: (b) hold
Explanation: The prize gave pride and courage to the people of Burma.
Q16. People of Burma sacrificed everything for a — Burma.
(a) happy
(b) autocratic
(c) democratic
(d) monarch
Correct Answer: (c) democratic
Explanation: They sacrificed their lives for democracy.
Q17. Aung San Suu Kyi is a —
(a) revolutionary
(b) classical dancer
(c) pro-democracy activist
(d) poetess
Correct Answer: (c) pro-democracy activist
Explanation: She worked for democracy and human rights through non-violence.
Q18. The act of willingly taking something offered is called —
(a) freedom
(b) democracy
(c) acceptance
(d) speech
Correct Answer: (c) acceptance
Explanation: Acceptance means willingly receiving something.
Q19. A person who lives in a monastery and has no possessions —
(a) monster
(b) monk
(c) mount
(d) activist
Correct Answer: (b) monk
Explanation: A monk is a religious person who lives a simple life in a monastery.
Q20. Let a new age —
(a) go
(b) come
(c) dawn
(d) up
Correct Answer: (c) dawn
Explanation: “Let a new age dawn” means let a new era begin.
Q21. The prize is intended to — all those engaged in struggle.
(a) honour
(b) thank
(c) engage
(d) indulge
Correct Answer: (a) honour
Explanation: The Nobel Prize honours people who struggle for peace and freedom.
Q22. ‘To pay attention’ means —
(a) greed
(b) to heed
(c) stand up
(d) give fees
Correct Answer: (b) to heed
Explanation: To heed means to pay attention or listen carefully.
Q23. Burmese people can hold their head —
(a) bigger
(b) shorter
(c) higher
(d) lower
Correct Answer: (c) higher
Explanation: It means they can feel proud.
Q24. The Nobel Prize ceremony is held on day of —
(a) freedom
(b) international human rights
(c) freedom struggle
(d) none
Correct Answer: (b) International Human Rights Day
Explanation: Nobel Peace Prize is awarded on 10 December, which is Human Rights Day.
Q25. ‘Incarcerated’ means —
(a) honoured
(b) dishonoured
(c) bailed
(d) jailed
Correct Answer: (d) jailed
Explanation: Incarcerated means imprisoned or jailed.
Q26. In Rangoon, in a heavily guarded compound, what was taking place?
(a) lonely struggle
(b) freedom
(c) democracy
(d) Nobel Prize
Correct Answer: (a) lonely struggle
Explanation: Aung San Suu Kyi was under house arrest and continuing her struggle for democracy.